(226, 1, '2015-05-12 20:31:27', '2015-05-12 20:31:27', 'It has been a while since web applications first began taking a major role in software development. Beginning as basic static pages with no interactions at all, web applications have since developed into highly complex, rich, and interactive digital organisms. Among this soup of new technologies, components and enhancements that facilitated this development, one of them stands out as a key factor making it all possible.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI still remember the days when Javascript was mainly used for client-side validations.  Remember how impressed we were?  Wow!  We could validate forms without wasting bandwidth with useless requests to the server!  Who would have imagined that only a few years later javascript could be used to run full applications on your browser?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBut as breakneck as this development has been, not everything has kept up at the same pace. It’s still common to come across some messy and poorly conceived/modularized Javascript code.  Poor testing practices are often at the root of this.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTesting -- I’m not talking about manually clicking randomly across your page looking for some weird behavior. Unit tests, navigation tests, integration tests, automated tests -- there’s a wide array of testing practices available so that product quality and efficiency can be ensured.  These tests that are typically employed to ensure the backend runs smoothly can also be applied to your front-end code.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-411 size-full" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/tests.png" alt="" width="494" height="330" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><b>Why testing?</b></h2>\r\nShort answer: to make sure it works.  Although we can rarely test our code to such an extent that it is guaranteed fail-proof, we can at least use testing to ascertain how a program will behave for certain given (expected) scenarios.  That’s already a LOT as you are cutting failure possibilities to edge cases (which you will create tests for in case they show up).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFront-end applications are complex; they have models, events, data handling and a bunch of other variables that can easily get out of hand if you don’t assure that functions are actually constrained to do what you have intended for them do.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTesting your code also provides a good way to determine how abstract and modularized your program is. The simple act of making code testable ensures that you are organizing your code with some kind of modularity. Try it. You’ll be thanking yourself in the future.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-406" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/yes-we-can.gif" alt="yes-we-can" width="800" height="300" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><b>So... How?</b></h2>\r\nHopefully this introduction convinced you of the importance of these tests. Now let’s talk about how they can actually be done. To make it less overwhelming I will split this into a series of posts that will walk you through the different processes. On this first post, I will explain each layer of our stack.  The following posts will elaborate on the variety of existing options and provide some tips on how to select the best one for your needs.\r\n<h2><b>A Typical Front-end Test Stack </b></h2>\r\n<h3><b>Test Framework</b></h3>\r\nThis component is responsible for making sure your tests will be run correctly. It does all the needed setup, loads dependencies, describes test suites, runs test cases and outputs results.\r\n<h3><b>Assertion Libraries</b></h3>\r\nThis provides the expectation language you will need to assert your test cases. This might seem simple to the point of triviality to you (and in most cases it actually is) but there are some cool and powerful extensions to these libraries that can sometimes be exactly what you need to best that “untestable” code.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-432" style="width: 540px !important;" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/qunit.png" alt="qunit" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Mocking Tools</b></h3>\r\nWhile it’s important to make everything work together, it’s also important to make sure every component can work properly when independently deployed. That’s why we need options to mock data or requests and simulate communication with other parties and assert our code behaves to all possible situations. The best part of this is that we can even simulate communication failures!\r\n<h3><b>Browsers / Automated tasks</b></h3>\r\nWe all know how boring it is to keep doing the same tests in different browsers. Why waste our time on these repetitive tasks when we can automate and let our machine do all the work for us?\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-448" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/test-diagram.png" alt="test-diagram" width="552" height="480" /></p>', 'Front-end tests: Yes we can!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '221-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:31:27', '2015-05-12 20:31:27', '', 221, 'http://localhost/acnew/221-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(227, 1, '2015-05-12 20:31:38', '2015-05-12 20:31:38', '', 'rubikscube_tissuebox_web', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'rubikscube_tissuebox_web-2', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:31:38', '2015-05-12 20:31:38', '', 222, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/rubikscube_tissuebox_web1.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(228, 1, '2015-05-12 20:31:40', '2015-05-12 20:31:40', 'This is the inaugural posting in a series of articles/tutorials/lessons (Or whatever synonymous term you would like to use!) aimed at illustrating how to design java software using Object Oriented Programming (OOP).  We will be modeling our problems to make them all as simple and palatable as mac &amp; cheese.\r\n\r\nBy the end of this 2-part article, you will understand how a simple software program works, how we design software to solve real-world problems, and something that would be a resume-builder for even the most seasoned professional: How to solve a Rubiks cube!\r\n\r\nUh… what?  Come on… You’re using a tech blog to talk about Rubiks cube?\r\n\r\nYeah!  In all seriousness, a Rubik’s cube is the perfect real-world example of an algorithm in action -- something that we can readily translate to software-ese…\r\n\r\nFirst, what is an algorithm?  An algorithm is an “effective method expressed as a finite list of well-defined instructions for calculating a function.”  In other (non-geek) words: It’s a set of instructions that set the rules for how something can be done.\r\n\r\nWhen you see someone solving a cube, they are in fact following some well-defined instructions, although they could be hyper-genius savants.\r\n\r\n<b>So Let’s get started!</b>\r\n\r\nThe first step is to fully understand what a Rubik’s cube is:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignleft" width="524"]<img src="http://www.youcandothecube.com/Themes/rubiks/img/content/solution-stage-one.jpg" alt="How to solve Rubik''s Cube - Stage 1" width="524" height="1426" /> source: http://www.youcandothecube.com/Themes/rubiks/img/content/solution-stage-one.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNice, huh?  I bet you never thought of a Rubik’s cube like this.\r\n\r\nThis also illustrates one of the crucial parts of our job: <b>Thinking of a good model for our problem.</b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBEFORE starting coding, its imperative that we UNDERSTAND the problem we’re dealing with.  This is where models come in handy.  First let’s talk about what a Rubik’s cube <i>really </i>is, broken down into its characteristic features, which we’ll call <b>PROPERTIES. </b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHere are some of the <b>PROPERTIES </b>of the Rubik’s cube:\r\n\r\n1. It is an object with 26 pieces: 6 center pieces, 12 edge pieces, and 8 corner pieces.\r\n\r\n2. Pieces can have 1 color (center pieces), 2 colors (edges) or 3 colors (corners)\r\n\r\n3. Each piece has a distinct position on the cube\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome of these properties are static:\r\n\r\nWe can’t change the amount of pieces.\r\n\r\nWe can’t change the colors on the pieces.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOthers are dynamic:\r\n\r\nWe can change the position of the pieces!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is good, because solving a Rubik’s cube requires that we move pieces around until all squares of a color are lined up on the same side of the cube.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs mentioned in the infographic, we have 12 possible movements (each of the 6 faces can be moved either clockwise or counterclockwise.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAny action that will <b>MODIFY </b>the object properties -- such as rotating a side of the cube -- we will call <b>METHODS</b>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnd how will we know that the cube is solved?  We will need to <b>CHECK </b>if all the pieces are in the correct place and <b>RETURN</b> an answer.  Anything that <b>RETURNS </b>an answer is called a <b>FUNCTION.  </b>\r\n\r\nTo explain the way this works, we will use a real life analog: simple exchange that goes on between our vision and our brains.  We must visually ascertain that the cube is complete by looking at it.  The visual image we see is then transferred in the form of electrical signals goes to our brains.  This process we might call the ‘check.’  Then the brain receives the image, and evaluates what it is seeing to determine whether the cube is complete or incomplete.  We can think of ‘Complete’ and ‘incomplete’ as values that are ‘returned’by the brain, which, in this analogy, would be the function<b>.  </b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCongratulations!  you just learned 3 crucial concepts in Object Oriented Modeling: <b>Properties, Methods, and Functions!</b>\r\n', 'Object Oriented Programming: Modeling (part 1)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '222-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:31:40', '2015-05-12 20:31:40', '', 222, 'http://localhost/acnew/222-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(229, 1, '2015-05-12 20:31:50', '2015-05-12 20:31:50', '', 'Turkey-waterfront_web', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'turkey-waterfront_web', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:31:50', '2015-05-12 20:31:50', '', 223, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Turkey-waterfront_web.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(230, 1, '2015-05-12 20:31:53', '2015-05-12 20:31:53', '<div style="color: #222222">This summer I visited Turkey and Greece for 2 weeks. I''ve always been fascinated with ancient cultural sites and images of waterfront life that countries in the region boast. I had a fascinating experience in Istanbul, looking at how well the old world co-exists with the new. I was quite surprised to see how well everything was maintained.</div> <br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-sunset.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-381" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-sunset-1024x491.jpg" alt="Istanbul sunset" width="600" height="288" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><br><br>\r\n<br><div>The waterfront cafes and districts that proliferate throughout the city are innumerable.</div><br>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Turkey-waterfront.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-384" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Turkey-waterfront-1024x662.jpg" alt="Turkey waterfront" width="600" height="388" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<br><div style="color: #222222">There are also older districts with cobblestones, shopping and street musicians that make summer nights amazing. I also visited the ancient historical site of Ephesus, which dates back to 7,000 years ago.</div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-Street-musicians.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-380" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-Street-musicians-1024x682.jpg" alt="Istanbul Street musicians" width="600" height="400" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<br><br><br><div style="color: #222222">Greece was a whole different experience.\r\n<div>Apart from visiting the Acropolis, I did not spend much time in Athens. Most of my time was spent on the Greek islands of Santorini and Ios.</div><br>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Greece-Acropolis-LR.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-379" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Greece-Acropolis-LR-1024x605.jpg" alt="Greece Acropolis LR" width="600" height="355" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222">Santorini is the image of Greece in the advertising world. With beautiful blue domed chapels<b>,</b> and whitewashed houses, this is island is entirely built on a ridge. Towns dot the length of the volcanic ridge, with gorgeous hotels clinging to the edges of the cliffs and offering spectacular views of the "caldera" or the bowl, dipping hundreds of feet down to the sea.</div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-383" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini-1024x682.jpg" alt="Santorini" width="600" height="400" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222">The sweet wine "Vin Santo" made in Santorini is  probably the most well known Greek wine, and touring the small wine trail and wine tasting there is very fun.</div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Wine-tasting-Santorini.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-385" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Wine-tasting-Santorini-1024x467.jpg" alt="Wine tasting Santorini" width="600" height="274" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><br>\r\n<div>Viewing the sunset is a tourist ritual in Oia<b>, </b>and draws claps and cheers.</div><br>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini-Sunset-LR.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-382" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini-Sunset-LR-1024x615.jpg" alt="Santorini Sunset LR" width="600" height="361" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div></div><br>\r\n<div>The water visibility in most of these places is pretty good. So I went scuba diving on a couple of different occasions both in Turkey and Greece, discovering a variety of ocean life.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222">These countries are very worth visiting. However, visiting outside of summer is probably better, if you don''t like crowded places.</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><img src="https://ci6.googleusercontent.com/proxy/RnNZfQn2o2xpggJQqefCOervMbPIci5mujDPJnvl43kv6Rtxjyh5gHN_JKVzeU-aaGz3pePFgxfoAAtZJZNx8mveVTc-11j98EfuAJVcumUenA=s0-d-e1-ft#https://ssl.gstatic.com/ui/v1/icons/mail/images/cleardot.gif" alt="" /></div>', 'Turkey, Greece, and their waterfront life', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '223-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:31:53', '2015-05-12 20:31:53', '', 223, 'http://localhost/acnew/223-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(231, 1, '2014-09-15 21:41:31', '2014-09-15 21:41:31', 'Over the past few years a lot of people have been trying to rethink the way the web can/should be used. Currently, front-end developers find themselves in the often-frustrating situation of having to build complex websites with HTML--which can often be a fairly blunt tool--on top of the clunky foundations of Jurassic-age web browser limitations.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="363"]<img src="http://jwmhs.pasco.k12.fl.us/wp-content/uploads/jwmhs/2013/11/calendar.png" alt="Calendar image" width="363" height="363" /> Source: http://jwmhs.pasco.k12.fl.us/wp-content/uploads/jwmhs/2013/11/calendar.png[/caption]\r\n\r\nLet’s start simple to illustrate the problem: Imagine that you are developing a website for airline tickets. As you are working, you decide that you would like to include a calendar in your webpage. Unfortunately, there’s no quick and easy way to create a calendar, using HTML. Instead, you will have to employ a variety of different elements to express this single concept. And if you need another calendar on the same page, you would have to repeat all those elements, and so on, for as many iterations as are needed.\r\n\r\nThere should be a simpler way to create something as simple and common as a calendar. And in fact there is. There are many 3rd-party libraries, (such as jQuery plugins), which can implement a calendar for you, but although these resources may save on coding time, at the end of the day they will add up to the same unwieldy mess of HTML elements in the page. The problems of coding while being limited to low-level elements are quickly compounded as ideas become more complex.\r\n\r\nBut let’s pause for a moment: How about this -- once we conceive of ‘calendar’ as a distinct concept, what if we could code calendar as a single element in HTML? Wouldn''t that be great?\r\n\r\nIn more general terms: is it possible to abstract low-level constructs of HTML to define high-level semantic components (such as calendars)?\r\n\r\nYes, it is possible! Or at least, it will be possible soon enough with <strong>Web Components</strong>.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/web-components.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-340" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/web-components.jpg" alt="web-components" width="500" height="500" /></a>\r\n\r\nSo what exactly are Web Components? Let''s drink it from the source, aka <a title="Introduction to Web Components" href="http://www.w3.org/TR/components-intro/" target="_blank">W3C specification for Web Components</a>:\r\n\r\nThe component model for the Web (also known as Web Components) consists of five harmoniously interacting pieces designed to enable Web application authors to define widgets with a level of visual richness and interactivity impossible to achieve with CSS alone, all with an ease of composition and reuse not possible with today’s existing script libraries.\r\n\r\nThe five pieces, at a glance, are:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/components-intro/" target="_blank">Templates</a>, which define chunks of markup that are inert but can be activated for use later.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/components-intro/" target="_blank">Decorators</a>, which apply templates based on CSS selectors to affect rich visual and behavioral changes to documents.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/components-intro/" target="_blank">Custom Elements</a>, which let authors define their own elements, with new tag names and new script interfaces.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/components-intro/" target="_blank">Shadow DOM</a>, which encapsulates a DOM subtree for more reliable composition of user interface elements.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/components-intro/" target="_blank">Imports</a>, which defines how templates, decorators and custom elements are packaged and loaded as a resource.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThese five pieces make it easier to make better things. Take our calendar example. Basically, a Web Component for a calendar would reduce all that HTML clutter to one, beautifully clean line of code:\r\n<pre style="overflow: auto;font-family: Consolas, ''Liberation Mono'', Menlo, Courier, monospace;font-size: 14px;margin-top: 0px;margin-bottom: 16px;font-style: normal;font-variant: normal;font-weight: normal;line-height: 1.45;padding: 16px;color: #333333;letter-spacing: normal;text-align: start;text-indent: 0px;background-color: #f7f7f7"><code style="font-family: Consolas, ''Liberation Mono'', Menlo, Courier, monospace;font-size: 14px;font-style: normal;font-variant: normal;font-weight: normal;line-height: inherit;padding: 0px;margin: 0px;border: 0px;background: transparent">&lt;x-calendar chosen="2013-06-09"&gt;&lt;/x-calendar&gt;</code></pre>\r\n(This is actually an existing open-source calendar web component, available at <a href="https://github.com/x-tag/calendar">https://github.com/x-tag/calendar</a>.)\r\n\r\nAs you can see, this encapsulated code is more capable of efficiently and meaningfully representing a high-level component such as a calendar. We no longer need to deal with low-level elements such as divs or spans, now that they have been internalized. It’s cleaner, and easier to maintain.\r\n\r\nWant to know how to use and develop a Web Component? Stay tuned on my next article about Web Components!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Web Components 101', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'web-components-101', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:17:11', '2015-05-18 17:17:11', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=231', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(232, 1, '2014-09-04 21:40:01', '2014-09-04 21:40:01', '<p style="text-align: center;">I was born in Scotland and spent three weeks there this Summer with my wife to celebrate our wedding anniversary. We were married immediately after we graduated from Edinburgh University and honeymooned in Scotland. As we were poor as church mice we had no money for a honeymoon, so a friend’s parents friend gave us a week in a cottage on a large estate in a Scottish countryside. The cottage was fully stocked and they were so nice it was a magical time.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Unfortunately over the years we lost track of our friend and were not sure where we had honeymooned. Our objective was to go to Scotland and find the cottage, celebrate with friends and do some sightseeing. Scotland is part of the United Kingdom (made up of Scotland, England, Wales and Northern Ireland). It is as far North as Juneau Alaska!! Fortunately the Gulf Stream keeps it warmer…… but that means that it rains a lot, in fact it rained 20 days out of 22 days that we were there.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00575.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-282" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00575-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00575" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">We did find the cottage, on the Ardverikie estate near Loch Laggan, here is a picture. The rest of the time we met friends and went sight seeing.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00592.jpeg"><img class="wp-image-283" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00592-168x300.jpeg" alt="DSC00592" width="300" height="533" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Scotland is famous for: <strong>Whisky</strong>, so we bought some really nice whisky, this was at the Dalwhinnie distillery, 900 dollars worth. It better taste REALLY good.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00628.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-284" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00628-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00628" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Golf</strong>, so I played in some of the best courses in the world, including Castle Stuart, where they play the Scottish open,</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00800.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-285" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00800-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00800" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Food</strong>, we had some truly special seafood, including this enormous lobster. This is my wife Evelyn and daughter Stephanie.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/haggis.jpg"><img class="wp-image-286" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/haggis.jpg" alt="haggis" width="600" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">and <strong>haggis</strong> of course, made from all the parts of a sheep that you would not normally eat.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00515.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-287" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00515-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00515" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">and we bought a new house (not):-)</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">If you are planning to go to Scotland, remember that it can be cold, and it might rain every day, but the scenery is stunning.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00509.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-288" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00509-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00509" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00512.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-290" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00512-1024x545.jpeg" alt="DSC00512" width="800" height="426" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00744.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-292" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00744-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00744" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00808.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-293" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00808-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00808" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00776.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-298" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00776-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00776" width="800" height="451" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/IMG_0729.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-299" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/IMG_0729-1024x768.jpeg" alt="IMG_0729" width="800" height="600" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">...and the people are very friendly.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00633.jpeg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-301" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00633-576x1024.jpeg" alt="DSC00633" width="576" height="1024" /></a>\r\nContact me if you are thinking about going to Scotland.</p>', 'Revisiting the Scottish Countryside', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'revisiting-the-scottish-countryside', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:18:05', '2015-05-18 17:18:05', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=232', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(233, 1, '2014-08-25 21:39:35', '2014-08-25 21:39:35', 'Many enterprise software developers still wonder why everyone is so concerned with client-side applications, HTML 5, Javascript, and front-end related "stuff." Such skills are very notable on job postings nowadays, even for enterprise development based on Java, .NET, and Rails (which are server-side technologies). A developer might ask: Why does nobody seem to care anymore that I have a Java architect certification if I don''t know about RequireJS, AngularJS or <em>whatever</em>JS (front-end development tools)?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe truth is that pretty much every enterprise software developer from the last decade should expect an evolution boom on the server-side development instead of the client-side. Just look at how Java, .NET, and Rails have developed across MVC frameworks, web services, cloud connectivity, security, multi-threading, and persistence. As if this wasn''t enough, server-side development trends towards SOA, ESB, EAI and clusterization are very notable as well. So what is going on?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAbout a decade ago, web applications started overtaking desktop applications (usually developed in Java Swing or VB.NET) in order to improve compatibility with the user''s computers. By adopting HTML for the user interface (UI), we no longer need to worry about the user''s operational system, as long as the user can access a web browser. This way, our software can even support mobile devices!￼\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow, let''s get back to the server-side enterprise development. While it is continuously evolving, it is still part of a web application bound to the same known limitations for the web such as request, response, session, cookies, and so on.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBuddy, you gotta trust me when I say the end user doesn''t care that the server-side is perfectly engineered when the client-side is sluggish—all that the user sees is the web application as a whole concept. This means that the user experience (UX) must be prioritized as well, otherwise this user might switch to another vendor with a more effective UI.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/infographic_v2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-200" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/infographic_v2-1024x819.jpg" alt="infographic_v2" width="796" height="637" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the web browser as the ultimate UI software, we need to overcome its limitations and provide the best possible UX in order to attract more users. And all they want are fully featured applications that are fast, responsive, and stable—as desktop applications have been in the past.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis, buddy, is what this fuss is all about—providing the desktop experience to the web user. This is the ultimate goal of every web application. This is the key to win the market.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAll in all, it comes down to a few line items:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Reducing the page load time.</strong> This can be achieved with a few optimization techniques such as compiling all JS files and CSS files to a single JS file and CSS file, minifying those files, compressing the response using gzip, and adopting a CDN (Content Distribution Network) to deliver such files from a server closer to the end user. All of this can be automatized using a task runner such as Grunt or Gulp.js.\r\n<strong>2. Reducing the response time from seconds to milliseconds.</strong> This can be achieved by using more AJAX to fetch only the data and leave the rendering to the browser. For this rendering we have Javascript template engines such as Mustache, Handlebars.js, dust.js, or Jade.\r\n<strong>3. Improving the navigation experience.</strong> This can be achieved by getting rid of page reloads, so the user would see the site as a SPA (Single-Page Application). For that we have Javascript MV* frameworks such as Backbone.js, AngularJS, Ember.js, or Knockout.\r\n<strong>4. Reducing the Javascript processing time.</strong> This can be achieved by adopting an asynchronous Javascript module loader such as RequireJS or YepNope. Favoring native browser features instead of depending on plugins such as Flash to render animations, audio, and video. This can now be achieved with HTML 5, CSS 3, SVG, and OpenGL.\r\n<strong>5. Adopting reusable components to improve semantics and save in downloaded content.</strong> A new universe of Web Components is coming out soon, and currently can be achieved with libraries such as Polymer and X-Tag.\r\n<strong>6. There is much more about optimizing web pages, so do your own research about other techniques available.</strong> Make sure you look at HTTP2 &amp; SPDY, WebSockets for transmitting binary data, localStorage, and offline mode.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMy final advice is that every type of software developer needs to learn more about all these new libraries and stay tuned to the front-end technologies. You won''t regret it—and nor will your resume!', 'What is all the fuss about with front-end development?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-all-the-fuss-about-with-front-end-development', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:18:19', '2015-05-18 17:18:19', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=233', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(234, 1, '2014-07-16 21:38:30', '2014-07-16 21:38:30', 'Process and software implementation methods have been improving around the world very fast over the past years.\r\nNot so long ago, one of the first known software development processes, which is still being used by lonely programmers or unorganized companies, is the empiric “Code and Fix” process that is nothing else than a process based on a trial  and error or an absence of process. Building software in this way, in some cases, ended up making the developer a true hero.\r\nA more civilized way to construct software emerged in the Waterfall process model, when it was realized that software construction is something that can be made step by step.  If well managed, allows more complex software to be constructed to accomplish specific goals never thought before.\r\nWith the Waterfall model, phases were defined to split and organize in a sequential order in the software life cycle. Every phase is accomplished sequentially where the next phase starts only when the current one ends.\r\nBig projects from huge companies emerged, but most failed. Why? The theory behind Waterfall process is pretty wonderful, but cost and time started to be a huge hurdle for this model and some of those projects that succeeded by being finished, were failing later because it was not attending to customer’s needs anymore.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Waterfall_model_%281%29.svg/350px-Waterfall_model_%281%29.svg.png" alt="" width="350" height="263" />\r\n\r\nAfter years using Waterfall model which compiled many failed projects, unsatisfied customers, and millions of dollars spent, many attempts raised to try to solve and revert bad image caused by the Waterfall model. As a good attempt, we can talk about the Iterative and Incremental model.\r\nWith the Iterative and Incremental model, the idea to divide and conquer emerged for large systems. One or more small pieces are produced to work and be used to increment the system at end of iteration.\r\nEvery iteration happens similar to waterfall model, but in this case to build a small piece of working software to be integrated with the whole. When the system is finished, if a small piece was to fail, the whole system might still work because every piece was created independently.\r\n\r\nAnother evolutionary approach is the Spiral model.  This combines aspects of iterative and waterfall models besides of a special emphasis in analysis and risk management. Every cycle of this model iterates through four quadrants as the project is incrementally developed: define objectives, alternatives and constraints; analyze risks; develop product; plan next cycle.\r\nThe spiral model wasn’t still a very good process model to be used widely around the world, because its costs was too high to be applied and is not a good option for small projects.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://www.designingprojectmanagement.com/images/Spiral%20process%20a%20software%20designing%20model.jpg" alt="" width="506" height="333" />\r\n\r\nGoing forward with more maturity and advanced practices, an evolved iterative and incremental process called RUP (Rational Unified Process), came up. Being Use Case and requirements driven, RUP which is based on the UP (Unified Process) model, utilizes Use Case to describe any interaction between the software system and anything external such as a user of the system. Use Cases are also very good to capture requirements in a way to provide a bird’s-eye view of the whole system, actors, external systems and interactions between.\r\n\r\nAnother good aspect of RUP is about the architecture whose try to describe static, dynamic, functional and non functional requirements of the overall system.\r\nWorking based on RUP theory seems to be wonderful on project’s world, with everything “well specified, well planned, well designed, and well tested.” The real world is pretty different. Mixed techniques started to be use. Engineers were trying to develop software using only the main parts of prior described process. Around the world they were trying to evolve software life cycle in a way to try to reduce costs and deliver  functional software faster.\r\nInitiatives like XP (eXtreme Programming) appeared and were well adopted by many companies and individual developers, to try to focus more on the code to create a final product. Agile movement were creating form. Other initiatives appeared to try to create architecture documentation, project management, tests and so on in a more agile way.\r\nAnother good example are the (Test Driven Development) TDD and more recently, (Acceptance Test Driven Development) ATDD, to try to produce code with automation tests to simplify integration process and bring agility. On TDD and ATDD the focus is to create the test cases, unity tests and integration tests before start codify client’s requirements.\r\nThe main idea of Agile is to drive software life cycle and delivery a functional product sooner. Agile does not try to eliminate documentation or methodology, but integrate team mates to communicate, follow and produce only what is crucial for some software project, creating the necessary documentation and doing all necessary steps to accomplish that project faster and with high quality.\r\n\r\nBy: Alexandre Menezes de Queiroz', 'Development of Software Implementation Methods', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'development-of-software-implementation-methods', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:18:32', '2015-05-18 17:18:32', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=234', 0, 'post', '', 0);
